      <hedline>
        <hl1>Decadence on Parade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Douglas W Tobin letter says that unbridled materialism and flaunting of new wealth makes it very difficult for teachers like himself to imbue students with strong moral values (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading your Dec. 26 Week in Review article ''When You Got It, Flaunt It,'' I could not help but fall into a state of moral despair and outrage.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading your Dec. 26 Week in Review article ''When You Got It, Flaunt It,'' I could not help but fall into a state of moral despair and outrage.</p>
        <p>To say that there is something profoundly wrong and potentially destructive with a society in which people send their linens to Paris to avoid a $6,000-a-month laundry bill; in which people buy sable coats for $150,000 each; in which pets have their own limousines, and in which children call ''their own town cars with their very own cellular phones'' would be an understatement. Yet, you say, ''charities nationwide report that donations from both individuals and companies are falling.''</p>
        <p>It is quite difficult for me and other teachers to imbue our students with strong moral values and ethical codes when they are continuously exposed to such insensitivity, greed, egocentricity and unbridled materialism.</p>
        <p>DOUGLAS W. TOBIN  New York, Dec. 28, 1999</p>
      </block>
